  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "    \nSynthesizer\n\n\n\n\n\nCycle of Life is a different version of the
    game originally called The Game of Life, also known as Conway's Game of Life
    or simply Life. It is a cellular automaton devised by the British mathematician
    John Horton Conway in 1970. It is a zero-player game, meaning that its evolution
    is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input. One interacts
    with the Game of Life by creating an initial configuration and observing how
    it evolves in discrete time steps called generations. There is no limit to the
    number of generations (computational resources permitting) or win condition.\n\nRules
    of the Game:\n-Birth Rule: An empty, or \u201Cdead\u201D cell with precisely
    three \u201Clive\u201D neighbors (full cells) becomes live.\n-Death Rule: A live
    cell with zero or one neighbors dies of isolation; a live cell with four or more
    neighbors dies of overcrowding.\n-Survival Rule: A live cell with two or three
    neighbors remains alive.\n\nHow to play:\n- Use the arrow keys or WASD to move
    around the area.\n- Use Mouse Editing Toggle to enable or disable mouse edit.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and left mouse button to create alive cells.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and right mouse button to kill alive cells.  \n-
    Select patterns from the pattern menu.\n- Adjust camera speed and zoom levels
    using the sliders.\n- Pause, resume, and reset the simulation using the buttons.\n-
    Change the theme by using theme button.\n\n    Cycle of Life is a different version
    of the game originally called The Game of Life, also known as Conway's Game of
    Life or simply Life. It is a cellular automaton devised by the British mathematician
    John Horton Conway in 1970. It is a zero-player game, meaning that its evolution
    is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input. One interacts
    with the Game of Life by creating an initial configuration and observing how
    it evolves in discrete time steps called generations. There is no limit to the
    number of generations (computational resources permitting) or win condition.\n\nRules
    of the Game:\n-Birth Rule: An empty, or \u201Cdead\u201D cell with precisely
    three \u201Clive\u201D neighbors (full cells) becomes live.\n-Death Rule: A live
    cell with zero or one neighbors dies of isolation; a live cell with four or more
    neighbors dies of overcrowding.\n-Survival Rule: A live cell with two or three
    neighbors remains alive.\n\nHow to play:\n- Use the arrow keys or WASD to move
    around the area.\n- Use Mouse Editing Toggle to enable or disable mouse edit.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and left mouse button to create alive cells.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and right mouse button to kill alive cells.  \n-
    Select patterns from the pattern menu.\n- Adjust camera speed and zoom levels
    using the sliders.\n- Pause, resume, and reset the simulation using the buttons.\n-
    Change the theme by using theme button.\n\n    Cycle of Life is a different version
    of the game originally called The Game of Life, also known as Conway's Game of
    Life or simply Life. It is a cellular automaton devised by the British mathematician
    John Horton Conway in 1970. It is a zero-player game, meaning that its evolution
    is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input. One interacts
    with the Game of Life by creating an initial configuration and observing how
    it evolves in discrete time steps called generations. There is no limit to the
    number of generations (computational resources permitting) or win condition.\n\nRules
    of the Game:\n-Birth Rule: An empty, or \u201Cdead\u201D cell with precisely
    three \u201Clive\u201D neighbors (full cells) becomes live.\n-Death Rule: A live
    cell with zero or one neighbors dies of isolation; a live cell with four or more
    neighbors dies of overcrowding.\n-Survival Rule: A live cell with two or three
    neighbors remains alive.\n\nHow to play:\n- Use the arrow keys or WASD to move
    around the area.\n- Use Mouse Editing Toggle to enable or disable mouse edit.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and left mouse button to create alive cells.\n-
    Drag mouse while holding CTRL and right mouse button to kill alive cells.  \n-
    Select patterns from the pattern menu.\n- Adjust camera speed and zoom levels
    using the sliders.\n- Pause, resume, and reset the simulation using the buttons.\n-
    Change the theme by using theme button."
